WEBVTT

00:02.258 --> 00:06.764
To start off with, could you give me some 
information about where you were born and when?

00:07.465 --> 00:10.910
Yes, Enid, Oklahoma, January 18th, 1939. My 
parents were both involved in the war. My father

00:17.078 --> 00:20.502
graduated from Enid Flying School with Advanced 
Air Force Base. He was killed as a B-17 pilot in

00:20.522 --> 00:24.988
World War II in England in 1944. My mother flew with 
Amelia Earhart's WASP, so she was gone. My

00:30.275 --> 00:31.557
grandparents raised me. I attended schools in 
Enid until I was having extreme difficulty

00:32.785 --> 00:43.701
growing up like most young men in about the ninth 
grade. Unlike a lot of young men, my father left me

00:45.083 --> 00:52.714
$10,000 insurance when he was killed. That's what 
the government paid then for your life. And I

00:55.719 --> 00:58.503
looked through Ladies Home Journal. I saw a lot of 
advertisements for preparatory schools. I wrote

01:02.013 --> 01:08.660
off to them, even though I was failing in the ninth 
grade, and received brochures back. I don't know

01:08.980 --> 01:18.830
why they accepted me, but I went to Fork Union 
Military Academy in Virginia from Oklahoma and

01:08.980 --> 01:18.830
did very well there. Whatever I may become, I have 
to give thanks to them because they certainly

01:19.571 --> 01:26.678
provided the foundation. I had an appointment to 
West Point since that was what I went to Fork Union

01:26.698 --> 01:30.602
for. I came back to Oklahoma, having graduated in 
the summer of 57, and applied for Texas A&M

01:31.477 --> 01:46.463
because, very frankly, I was burned out on gray, 
stiff wool uniforms. And I just couldn't see

01:47.084 --> 01:50.470
myself starting over another four years that way. 
The Texas A&M Corps, as I remember in those days,

01:51.632 --> 01:55.999
had almost 6,000. was one of the most famous corps 
in the United States. And I decided I want to be a

01:59.876 --> 02:01.858
part of the best. That's why I applied. But I was 
really a young man rolling around looking for a

02:05.402 --> 02:09.486
hole to fall into. And before I could get down here 
at Texas A&M, I went over and joined the

02:10.387 --> 02:14.372
paratroops. And that was in August of 1957.

02:21.460 --> 02:49.493
even with all my military training the fact that 
i've probably forgotten more about some of the

02:21.460 --> 02:49.493
weapons having been trained in the rotc program 
and some of the sergeants for example my drill

02:21.460 --> 02:49.493
sergeant had been a locomotive engineer and knew 
nothing about what we were doing and i was always a

02:21.460 --> 02:49.493
trainee platoon sergeant in my individual and 
advanced training i was court-martialed twice in

02:21.460 --> 02:49.493
the first eight weeks

02:21.460 --> 02:49.493
so i got kind of started off on a bad foot even though 
At the end of the first eight weeks, the command

02:49.996 --> 02:53.820
wanted to send me to OCS. I refused to go because I 
wanted to be in Special Forces, more than I wanted

02:54.761 --> 02:58.785
to be an officer. So I ended up in Special Forces at 
Fort Bragg as a demolitionist. And the only reason

03:05.052 --> 03:10.378
I really became a Ranger, or became an officer, is 
because I wanted to be a Ranger. And I kept applying

03:11.158 --> 03:18.366
for Ranger training, and Special Forces didn't 
receive Ranger training those days, since we got

03:11.158 --> 03:18.366
it as part of our normal day-to-day duties. 
Finally, Sergeant Ortiz, the 77th, said, Bo, if

03:20.850 --> 03:26.758
you want to go to Ranger school, you got to be a 
second lieutenant. I said, well, make me a second

03:27.179 --> 03:28.681
lieutenant. So he gave me the forms for OCS. I 
filled them out. I went to OCS. I went to Ranger

03:34.229 --> 03:35.190
training. And following that, I found out 
something. I couldn't get back in Special Forces

03:38.855 --> 03:42.761
because there were no second lieutenants in 
Special Forces. That's all I really cared about

03:43.682 --> 03:46.406
was being there. So after I made first lieutenant, 
I went back to Special Forces. And then in 1964, I

03:50.928 --> 03:57.936
went to Vietnam and served four years in Vietnam. 
My jobs included being the chief of

03:58.497 --> 04:11.072
reconnaissance and the intelligence officer for 
Project Delta, which at that time was the only one

03:58.497 --> 04:11.072
of the super secret organizations that was in 
operation. Our job was to go into denied areas and

04:11.112 --> 04:15.657
obtain intelligence. Following that, I 
organized at the direction of General

04:16.717 --> 04:25.405
Westmoreland the first American commanded 
guerrilla force. And it was supposed to have been a

04:25.425 --> 04:32.551
volunteer operation where once we tested it, we 
would all get our choice of assignments. We know

04:32.571 --> 04:33.432
how that works. If you're successful, they want 
you to stay together for one more, for one more, for

04:33.492 --> 04:37.796
one more. So four operations later, we had finally 
completed our guerrilla mission. It was during

04:43.161 --> 04:44.142
that time We recovered the U-2 that General Russ 
Mullen writes about in his book, A Soldier

04:44.560 --> 04:49.188
Reports. That was just one of our training 
missions. Following that, General Wyatt asked me

04:53.034 --> 05:00.647
to form a unit that could do a myriad of special 
activities. For example, blowing up bridges at

05:00.867 --> 05:06.757
the Air Force where it was having difficult 
hitting, raiding enemy headquarters. Gorillas

05:06.777 --> 05:08.620
are two and a half miles an hour. They're limited by 
foot power. And they don't travel very fast.

05:12.840 --> 05:13.941
They're not very responsive. Plus, we couldn't 
keep our prisoners alive. And they wanted

05:16.304 --> 05:19.468
prisoners from various areas. So we restructured 
the guerrilla command into what was called a

05:20.009 --> 05:26.757
special task force B-36. And I formed that. As 
cannon fodder, I required five Americans from

05:30.442 --> 05:36.770
each of the infantry divisions, five LURPs. The 
general wanted to know if I wanted sergeants. They

05:39.773 --> 05:41.095
were airborne ranger. And I said, no, because the 
division commanders will never give them up.

05:45.302 --> 05:46.403
Those are their prized people. I said, I just want 
somebody who is long-range reconnaissance

05:46.423 --> 05:50.969
patrol qualified. Part of my Delta duties was to 
train LRPS. And so I was a chief instructor at the

05:55.534 --> 06:00.199
Rekondo School in Vietnam until we formed the 
guerrilla command. B-36 was very successful at

06:02.081 --> 06:04.804
what we did. it was at the end of four years i had just 
put in for an extension leave i was working for

06:05.392 --> 06:32.766
general wyatt on special operations and i went to 
him with a proposal because i was using cambodians

06:05.392 --> 06:32.766
i didn't speak cambodia and our missions were 
extremely high visibility i wanted to obtain a

06:05.392 --> 06:32.766
force that i could communicate with because 
frequently more fire came from behind us than came

06:05.392 --> 06:32.766
from the front of us meaning the cambodes that 
followed you directly behind you were fine but

06:33.083 --> 06:53.826
those on the flanks often were behind you and 
didn't know what was going on so you had as much

06:33.083 --> 06:53.826
danger of being shot from the rear as you did in the 
front in many cases so i asked him if i could have the

06:33.083 --> 06:53.826
prisoners out of long been jail since they their 
lives were basically finished And in about 30 or 60

06:54.245 --> 06:57.209
days, I could train them as guerrillas. And they 
spoke English. And we could probably have

07:00.535 --> 07:05.442
increased our productivity some 300, 400%. It was 
at that time that Wyatt changed my mind and showed

07:06.464 --> 07:12.152
me the light about Vietnam. He said, quote, Bo, 
stop trying to win the war. You're not going to win

07:16.759 --> 07:17.781
it. I'm not going to win it. Use this war to benefit 
your career. He said, be ahead of your

07:23.067 --> 07:26.492
contemporaries. Come up on the general staff. 
I'll give you a job here. Use the war to get your

07:30.417 --> 07:34.323
promotions earlier than those that aren't over 
here. And it just thunderstruck me because we were

07:35.264 --> 07:41.874
in the field dying and trying. And I said to him, 
yes, sir, I know that I can't win the war by myself,

07:42.755 --> 07:50.526
and even you as the daddy rabbit can't win it. But if 
we don't try every day as hard as we can, the thing

07:50.962 --> 07:54.427
will never be over. But I realized then that he had, 
being the commander, he knew things that I didn't

07:55.128 --> 08:01.458
know. There was no intent of winning that war. And I 
decided instantly that I would not be responsible

08:04.042 --> 08:10.471
for one life, one limb, one liberty being lost 
again. So I left Vietnam and came back to the United

08:11.313 --> 08:16.260
States very disillusioned. And it's ironic, 
because over my headquarters, some of my

08:17.050 --> 08:26.449
sergeants had placed this plaque that we took with 
us, my headquarters, wherever we happened to set

08:17.050 --> 08:26.449
up in the jungle. But it had four lines. The first 
line said, we come because we believe. And that's

08:31.298 --> 08:31.859
true. We were all there because we believed in what 
we were doing. The second line said, we leave

08:35.246 --> 08:38.873
because we're disillusioned. And that's 
precisely what I did. The third line, I almost

08:41.733 --> 08:44.757
succumbed to, too. It said, we return because 
we're lost. And the last line said, we die because

08:47.921 --> 08:50.825
we're committed. And that is exactly what 
happened to many of those brave soldiers there who

08:51.826 --> 08:59.376
stayed with me over those periods of time. They'd 
get disillusioned. They'd go home. Next thing you

09:01.479 --> 09:03.261
know, here they'd be back again. The next thing you 
know, they're in a body bag. And I almost

09:06.225 --> 09:07.527
succumbed. fit that scenario myself. When you 
come back from the war, what does the Army do with

09:10.184 --> 09:14.170
you? Most 19-year-old kids who came back, and 
that's what the average age was in Vietnam, flew.

09:20.460 --> 09:24.306
It took them 19 hours to get in the combat zone to 
Travis Air Force Base. When they got there, they

09:25.027 --> 09:32.980
were given a piece of paper and said, thank you, 
patted on the ass, and left to figure out what had

09:25.027 --> 09:32.980
happened to them for the last year. And in that very 
traumatic part of their life. When most kids were

09:36.917 --> 09:45.465
going to trade school, going to college, or 
figuring out what they wanted to be when they grow

09:36.917 --> 09:45.465
up, these kids were over there watching their 
friends get their heads blown off. And it affects

09:45.485 --> 09:49.909
you, especially at that young age. I was a 
professional, had been through every combat

09:50.009 --> 09:55.134
school that the military had when I went there. I 
was prepared for Vietnam, except I hadn't had that

09:56.295 --> 10:01.480
acid test. I craved it. I was there because I should 
have been there. and because I wanted to be there.

10:07.714 --> 10:15.703
At any rate,

10:07.714 --> 10:15.703
I was really affected at four years of doing 
nothing but killing the enemy every day. It's a

10:16.344 --> 10:24.613
very, for lack of a better term, fearful when I 
thought about coming back to the United States.

10:25.094 --> 10:26.696
What do those people have in common with me? What is 
my role there? Who am I there? I knew who I was in

10:30.360 --> 10:32.523
Vietnam. I knew what my role was. It was very clear. 
What am I going to do in the United States? How do I

10:38.875 --> 10:39.695
relate? Because to me that was the unreal world. We 
were committed in Vietnam, committed to winning

10:42.499 --> 10:46.823
that war, and whatever that meant. So when I came 
back, the Army was very good to me. They first of all

10:50.627 --> 10:53.731
sent me to a year and a half of Chinese language 
school. God knows that was the hardest thing that

10:54.391 --> 10:57.375
I've ever done. I guess for damn near 18 hours a day, 
because that's what it takes to study Chinese.

11:04.062 --> 11:09.669
trying to defuse me, bring my RPMs down from red 
line to idle. And following that, I went to Command

11:09.689 --> 11:13.713
General Staff College. I graduated, honored 
graduate of the Command General Staff College.

11:18.219 --> 11:22.964
When I finished that, again, I applied for duty in 
Vietnam. And my best friend, who will be the chief

11:22.984 --> 11:29.412
of staff in the Army someday, said, Bo, please 
don't go back there. And I see now that it perfectly

11:30.185 --> 11:33.809
met that equation. We returned because we're 
lost. And I said, no, I've got to go back over there.

11:39.755 --> 11:44.800
As long as that war is there, I cannot have let my 
friends have died in vain. We must win that war. He

11:49.724 --> 11:50.605
talked me out of that. He said, Bo, that's crap. 
Stay here. You're only going to lose over there.

11:58.298 --> 11:59.720
And I listened to him. I listened to him again when 
he told me to marry the wife that I have now. And he

12:02.543 --> 12:03.765
was right about that, too. So anyway, the Army sent 
me to school, having gone through about three

12:04.806 --> 12:11.694
years of defusing. But even when I was in the 
Command General Staff College, I, at nighttime,

12:12.235 --> 12:19.484
would shoot the lights out in the town of 
Leavenworth. I'm sure the prison geared up 100

12:19.504 --> 12:24.610
times when I would come home at night. Tucson, 
Arizona didn't have very many streetlights in it.

12:27.159 --> 12:28.341
I didn't put bullet holes through. For about three 
years as a field grade officer, I was doing things

12:28.381 --> 12:35.572
like that because it was still the year of the gun. 
And people just tolerated me. I guess I never had

12:38.636 --> 12:40.459
any trouble with anybody. I threw colonels over 
the bar at Fort Leavenworth. It was just the nature

12:45.106 --> 12:47.710
of the beast then. So... And then ironically 
enough I was given a job on the art. Well, I was

12:53.445 --> 12:59.012
supposed to go with Nixon to China Because he was 
when he made his trip over there. He was going over

12:59.032 --> 13:09.425
to establish a US mission He thought but the 
Chinese weren't ready for that yet So I was

12:59.032 --> 13:09.425
selected as because they didn't have an old seven 
which was a Brigadier General. They were looking

13:09.445 --> 13:20.078
for that spoke Chinese they tagged me to go and Then 
it fell apart because the Chinese weren't going to

13:09.445 --> 13:20.078
cooperate with Nixon that quickly As a result, I 
said, what do I do now? I had jobs because I had

13:23.886 --> 13:29.312
graduated high in the CNGS, any place I wanted it. I 
ended up on the Army General Staff working for

13:29.912 --> 13:32.735
General Westmoreland. He said he wanted someone 
as a spokesman for the Army who had decorations on

13:33.376 --> 13:39.382
their chest and not a journalist. And his job, even 
though he hated it at that time, he directly

13:40.704 --> 13:45.929
opposed it, was to sell the Modern Volunteer Army. 
And it was my job to act as as his spokesman in doing

13:50.045 --> 13:51.486
that. I believed in it, because I didn't want 
anything but volunteers around me. But he showed

13:55.790 --> 13:59.093
me where I was very tunnel visioned. And where the 
modern volunteer army doesn't work, we should

13:59.113 --> 14:02.296
have the draft. And he's right, because we have cut 
out that cross-section of American society that

14:02.336 --> 14:12.986
keeps America interested in what the military is 
doing and keeps the army a part of society instead

14:02.336 --> 14:12.986
of apart from it. So at any rate, at that time, 
General Abrams came on board. And Abrams hated

14:19.559 --> 14:21.443
special forces. And so he took one look at me and 
said, I've got nothing to say to you. And a good

14:27.077 --> 14:30.866
friend of mine, General Seidel, asked me, he said, 
Bo, how would you like to go to school? So again,

14:31.447 --> 14:35.577
when they don't have anything for a soldier to do, 
they send him to school. As a result, I became

14:36.316 --> 14:54.617
highly degreed as a victim of circumstance, and I 
really haven't used any of the scholastic talents

14:36.316 --> 14:54.617
other than the bits of trivia that help you in your 
day-to-day life.

14:54.637 --> 15:03.808
After finishing the school, I was selected to go 
down and command the Special Forces in Panama, and

14:54.637 --> 15:03.808
I did that for two years. It was there that General 
Harold R. Aaron, who was a major general then,

15:04.345 --> 15:10.191
first contacted me. He was the chief of military 
intelligence then. He came to Panama and he asked

15:13.434 --> 15:21.982
me to think about how we might be able to gain 
information on American POWs in Southeast Asia.

15:23.123 --> 15:27.988
It totally dumbfounded me because I was a 
commander of special forces in Panama. I was

15:28.448 --> 15:33.373
concerned only about Latin America, the 
strategic protection of the Canal Zone, and all

15:33.809 --> 15:36.513
this other kind of crap. He was talking about last 
life, you know, Vietnam. And I remember when he

15:41.741 --> 15:47.570
left, I told my intelligence officer, Randy 
Young, the general's clutches slipping. You

15:47.790 --> 15:50.054
know, he's back in Vietnam. I was inexplicably 
transferred to the Office of the Secretary of

15:50.074 --> 15:58.407
Defense, much against General McAuliffe, who was 
the sink south. Objections. He wanted me to stay

15:59.048 --> 16:01.892
down there in Panama, but... OSD, somebody 
pressed a button. I ended up going to the Defense

16:05.966 --> 16:14.716
Security Assistance Agency as the Congressional 
Relations Chief. And General Fish was my

16:14.736 --> 16:18.180
commander there. When I said, what the hell am I 
doing in Washington, D.C. as Congressional

16:18.801 --> 16:22.165
Relations? I'm a jungle fighter. And he said, Bo, 
you'll find your assignment here is much like that

16:23.887 --> 16:31.255
that you're used to, the jungles of Washington. 
are just different in that they're concrete, but

16:31.640 --> 16:38.452
they're still insidious, and they're still 
dangerous, and we need your kind of skills here.

16:40.495 --> 16:45.003
The committee that I worked with was a foreign 
relations committee, both in the House and the

16:40.495 --> 16:45.003
Senate. They have oversight for the POW issue. It 
was in October of 1978 when Aaron came to me. Now

16:53.056 --> 16:57.664
he's a lieutenant general, and the number two man 
in the Defense Intelligence Agency said, Bo,

16:58.150 --> 17:01.333
we've got overwhelming evidence that Americans 
are still being held. We'd like you to consider

17:01.353 --> 17:10.942
retirement so that you can work through the 
private sector because the Carter

17:01.353 --> 17:10.942
administration has politically handcuffed us 
from doing anything about the POW issue. I was to

17:12.304 --> 17:15.167
take a hiatus in my military career. It didn't turn 
out that way. It's been five years. I will not go

17:18.810 --> 17:20.231
back in uniform. I don't think. The reason the FBI 
asked me in January of 1983, Bo, are you ready to

17:22.954 --> 17:28.039
come back in uniform now? I said, no. He said, why? I 
said, because the job's not over. And I caveated

17:32.314 --> 17:36.159
that further by saying, I don't think I will 
either. And the guy says, why not? Because at the

17:40.043 --> 17:45.189
time of my retirement, I was at the very good times 
of your career. You work hard in the Army to finally

17:45.650 --> 17:48.273
get someplace. And I had finally gotten to the 
point where the Army was going to be fun for me. and

17:52.910 --> 18:17.652
then to give it up right at that time didn't make 
sense matter of fact army times ran a big front page

17:52.910 --> 18:17.652
article when i retired that said it was a surprise 
it was and nobody believed the reasons i gave and

17:52.910 --> 18:17.652
they were right but i couldn't tell them why i 
retired at that time bottom line is that it is far

17:52.910 --> 18:17.652
more important that this issue be resolved 
correctly for the good of the nation than it is for

18:18.037 --> 18:25.904
any one person to have fun with the Army. And for 
that reason, as an urge in my conscience, I cannot

18:26.945 --> 18:34.673
quit until this thing is resolved 
satisfactorily. I will not quit. So far I've had no

18:36.795 --> 18:39.157
one ask me to quit. I think that secretly each one of 
the people in the bureaucracy hopes that we will

18:39.978 --> 18:45.343
succeed. I know that not so secretly, many people 
in the military, especially Fort Bragg, my

18:46.066 --> 19:00.465
contemporaries, embrace me when I go to see them in 
the Pentagon, are praying that we will be

18:46.066 --> 19:00.465
successful because they know what we're doing is 
right. So that's without stopping. a capsule of

