couple of times that I was I was approaching 
insanity over there from that point of view when

19:59.877 --> 20:23.995
suddenly you would see a man that was a living human 
being who had a family just like yours who had

19:59.877 --> 20:23.995
aspirations and hope for life One moment when 
you're in ambush, he is there thinking, living,

20:24.532 --> 20:34.583
feeling, and the next moment he's garbage, laying 
along the trail. It makes you realize that

20:36.585 --> 20:40.129
something is not right about it. And as a soldier, 
you're doing your job. Thank God, because when I

20:44.613 --> 20:53.543
finished the war, when I left, I had a terrible 
time, as I said, coming back to the United States,

20:44.613 --> 20:53.543
trying to find My handhold here. One of the first 
things I did is I came back and I went home to Tucson,

20:58.386 --> 21:10.339
Arizona, where my mother then lived, and tried to 
come to grips before my language school started. I

21:10.419 --> 21:12.241
had about a month and a half. I ended up going up on a 
mountain in northern Mexico by myself because

21:12.261 --> 21:18.708
there was nobody here who could help me. Nobody 
here knew what my problem was. Nobody had ever been

21:22.111 --> 21:23.513
a part of it. I married a Chinese girl and brought 
her back with me, a Chinese ethnic, Vietnamese

21:24.033 --> 21:33.126
origin, because she was the only one who knew who I 
was. She was my identity. She knew how hard we had

21:34.969 --> 21:36.491
tried. She knew my friends who had died. I needed 
her as my ID card. It didn't work out, even though I

21:42.860 --> 21:46.205
did get two wonderful kids from her. But I went up on 
the mountain to find out, one, if there was a chance

21:47.366 --> 21:53.415
that I had a life, I was raised in Pentecostal 
churches in Oklahoma, and you're not supposed to

21:54.003 --> 22:04.013
kill people, let alone hundreds of them. And you 
have to reconcile yourself. When I went up there, I

22:06.716 --> 22:14.584
took one bullet in my 9mm, not to protect me against 
the wolves, because certainly if they were going

22:06.716 --> 22:14.584
to eat you, they were going to eat you. But as a final 
determiner, If I couldn't have reconciled myself

22:19.923 --> 22:32.783
and saw that I do have a good life to live, then I 
would have started as quickly as I could whatever

22:19.923 --> 22:32.783
comes after. The fact is that a lot of things did 
come very clear to me, I had to answer the questions

22:39.953 --> 22:41.736
Why do people die like that? Is it all right for a 
soldier to take those lives? Why do babies have to

22:46.083 --> 22:47.606
die? There are all kinds of those questions that 
many Vietnam vets had to answer. I was lucky enough

22:51.793 --> 22:54.898
because I had the intelligence. I went up there. I 
got those answers. When I came down, I was a whole

22:59.085 --> 23:02.350
human being again. I was still pretty frisky, like 
I say. I shot out a lot of streetlights. I threw a lot

23:06.327 --> 23:11.514
of people over the bars, but I was settled in my 
life. That saved me. So Vietnam gave me a positive

23:15.300 --> 23:22.270
thing in that it gave me the secret to life, and that 
is a paradox. Many things are paradoxes about

23:23.051 --> 23:25.114
combat. If you're going to live, you must choose 
the road to death. That may not sound right. But it

23:31.253 --> 23:34.638
simply means if you're going to live, you can't be 
thinking about home. You can't be thinking about

23:35.099 --> 23:38.143
wife, family, D-Rose. Before I would go on a 
mission, I would see myself being killed in every

23:38.164 --> 23:42.991
conceivable way. That way I had already died by 
parachute crashing into the trees or into a band of

23:43.812 --> 23:54.729
cobras or being blown apart as I hung in the trees by 
the enemy machine gunner. Having already died

23:55.330 --> 23:59.556
those ways, then there's no place for the enemy's 
bullet. And so when you go into combat, you have

24:00.295 --> 24:04.221
chosen the road to death. You're much more alert. 
Hopefully the enemy is thinking about home or what

24:05.783 --> 24:12.634
he's going to do when he gets back. And in that 
moment is when the bullet enters his brain and

24:12.734 --> 24:19.004
stops his life. So there are many of those 
paradoxes, but yes, there are. I gained the secret

24:23.195 --> 24:27.100
of life through learning about death. What 
specifically did you do in Vietnam, and what unit

24:28.461 --> 24:32.626
were you in? Okay, to give you specifics, when I 
first went over there, I organized a camp called

24:33.568 --> 24:39.134
Sui Da. Sui Da means Rock Creek. It's next to Nui Ba 
Den Mountain, which is very famous in Vietnam as a

24:40.636 --> 24:44.841
shrine. Nui Ba Den means the Black Virgin 
Mountain. My unit was called A322. Later, I went to

24:52.034 --> 25:05.811
Delta Project as the first officer who was the 
reconnaissance chief, and I was called

24:52.034 --> 25:05.811
Detachment B-52, and I was the reconnaissance 
chief and the intelligence officer for Project

24:52.034 --> 25:05.811
Delta. Then I was the chief instructor of the McVie 
Recondo School. Following that, I formed The

25:15.625 --> 25:18.429
guerrilla task force called 957. That means 21 as 
blackjack as a winner. That's why it came about

25:22.013 --> 25:25.097
like that. Later, it turned into Detachment B-36, 
Special Task Force B-36. And later, that turned

25:31.646 --> 25:34.490
into the 3rd Mobile Strike Command. If you look in 
the lineage of Vietnam, I formed each one of those

25:35.251 --> 25:40.538
units. And then after they were formed, I 
eventually left them. I left the 3rd Mobile Strike

25:44.127 --> 25:48.852
Command after becoming disillusioned in 
November of 1968.

25:51.875 --> 25:54.378
And I was the commander of each one of them. Each one 
of them contained American troops. I had one of the

25:58.702 --> 26:01.605
very unique commands in Vietnam. In B-36, for 
example, I had

26:01.705 --> 26:11.215
five companies of Chinese that we used as security 
forces. I had eight companies of Cambodians that

26:11.971 --> 26:16.275
we used as guerrilla forces. I had about 50 
American special forces that made up special

26:17.697 --> 26:23.522
teams. And I had five LURPs from each infantry 
division that made up my reconnaissance unit. And

26:29.568 --> 26:31.991
I had a team of SAS from the Australians. So I had a 
real cross-section of everybody there. So that's

26:39.157 --> 26:40.358
what it was all about. What was the motivation, 
your motivation to your valor in Vietnam in which

26:41.119 --> 26:48.406
you received all these 60 decorations? Just doing 
the job. It's very hard for Special Forces to be

26:51.349 --> 26:54.152
decorated in Vietnam. The reason is because in the 
divisions, a two-star general is authorized to

26:54.432 --> 27:00.058
give up to a silver star. We had no two-star 
generals in Special Forces. So if we were going to

27:04.782 --> 27:07.645
get a decoration, General Westmoreland had to 
give it. General Westmoreland didn't have much

27:08.418 --> 27:14.648
time, being the daddy rabbit, to deal with Special 
Forces. So much of the things that Special Forces

27:15.329 --> 27:19.836
did went totally unsung. For example, we got 
nothing for recovering the U-2. You'd have

27:23.301 --> 27:24.863
thought that would have been a big deal. It was big 
enough for him to single it out as the example of the

27:25.765 --> 27:34.078
American soldier, but no decorations were given 
for that U-2 operation. Nobody thinks about the

27:34.098 --> 27:36.822
soldier when he's doing his job. we were just there 
doing the job trying to win the war and the

27:38.253 --> 28:07.720
decorations that i received came from generals 
that we worked for because they were astounded by

27:38.253 --> 28:07.720
our work general hay commanding general first 
division for example gave me two silver stars in in

27:38.253 --> 28:07.720
one day and said bo i wish that there was some higher 
decoration we could give your command he lined my

27:38.253 --> 28:07.720
whole command up and awarded silver stars He said, 
but this is the highest award I can give you. He

28:10.769 --> 28:13.432
says, what you people are doing is amazing. I don't 
know how you do that. He said, what do you eat, for

28:15.534 --> 28:17.196
example? I pulled out a package of indigenous 
ration, which was dried rice and minnows. He said,

28:23.462 --> 28:26.725
God, we could never feed Americans that. But see, 
he forgets that special forces are Americans,

28:26.745 --> 28:29.228
too. So the lines of our motto, We came because we 
believed. We were there because we believed in

28:40.752 --> 28:42.995
each other. And once you start it, it is a 
continuous cycle. How do you end it? We had to make

28:50.526 --> 29:00.341
sure, it seemed to me, that the men who had 
sacrificed their life, their limbs, their

28:50.526 --> 29:00.341
liberties, didn't do so in vain. That meant one 
thing, victory. There is no in-between. It's

29:04.567 --> 29:05.989
victory or it's defeat. And I was resolved to stay 
there the duration, plus six, whatever that

29:07.015 --> 29:12.323
meant. One of the big mistakes we made in Vietnam 
was that we sent generals there for one year. And a

29:18.452 --> 29:24.481
general going there for one year figured, geez, if 
I don't do anything, maybe I won't do anything

29:18.452 --> 29:24.481
wrong. And the generals should have all gone 
there, like we did in World War II. You come home

29:29.308 --> 29:30.930
when the job is done. But we were trying to get 
everybody through the combat experience.

29:35.836 --> 29:40.706
Everybody came over there looking to enhance 
their career by spending one year in a combat zone.

29:41.307 --> 29:48.261
And then, like General Wyant said, using it as part 
of your ticket punching to get ahead of your

29:41.307 --> 29:48.261
contemporaries. So I had all my tickets punched. I 
got advanced degrees. I've been on the Army

29:52.970 --> 30:01.142
general staff, the Office of the Secretary of 
Defense staff, all of the Army schools where I

29:52.970 --> 30:01.142
graduated, honored graduate from. And even all 
that ticket punching isn't enough to override my

30:01.843 --> 30:12.479
conscience, because I know what must be done in 
this case. And I was wrong about Vietnam. We

30:15.784 --> 30:17.927
shouldn't have been there. being there we should 
have won it and it was only when i realized that was

30:18.380 --> 30:31.917
impossible that i was not going to continue to 
throw good energy after bad and i quit

30:34.276 --> 30:35.718
You just mentioned the generals. If we could do it 
all over again, what do you feel the United States

30:36.158 --> 30:41.164
should do to win the war? Well, I think the first 
thing is the United States should not have fought a

30:41.724 --> 30:45.469
war in the first place. I think the United States 
has an obligation to wake up. I'm so damn mad at the

30:49.653 --> 30:54.499
American people because we have become a nation of 
spectators. We lay back and we love to be

30:55.260 --> 31:01.026
entertained, but we've forgotten and we 
criticize the government. But the government is

31:01.478 --> 31:05.450
of the people, by the people, and for the people. 
And we forget that. Those people working in

31:06.793 --> 31:10.344
Washington, D.C. are elected by us and work for us. 
If they do something wrong, damn it, it's our

31:10.705 --> 31:13.874
fault. And participative government has become a 
thing of the past. And so if we educate ourselves,

31:17.071 --> 31:22.580
we are obligated as a nation to know what the hell is 
going on. If we would have done our homework about

31:23.101 --> 31:28.270
Vietnam, we would have found out that we should 
have never been there in the first place. In 1944,

31:28.610 --> 31:31.916
Ho Chi Minh embraced us. The OSS trained Ho Chi 
Minh. We gave him equipment. He loved the

31:35.963 --> 31:37.205
Americans. The war was won in 1945. Instead of the 
United States taking over the... the transition

31:43.632 --> 31:51.207
of government in Southeast Asia, they turned it 
over to the British because our primary effort was

31:43.632 --> 31:51.207
in Japan and in Europe. When the British took over, 
it was decided for some moment of insanity that we

31:52.369 --> 32:01.708
would give the control of Southeast Asia back to 
the French. Ho Chi Minh then tapped us on the

32:02.448 --> 32:06.513
shoulder and says, what are you doing? Are you 
going to stand by and let them recolonize our

32:06.573 --> 32:11.138
countries? We should have our independence. The 
Japanese gave us the independence, for Christ's

32:12.500 --> 32:15.323
sake. But the United States would not intervene. 
We didn't even weigh in with the British in De

32:19.448 --> 32:23.573
Gaulle about that. We just turned our head away 
from Ho Chi Minh and said, sorry, we can't hear you,

32:23.734 --> 32:28.379
Ho. As a result, the French took over again. As a 
result, Ho Chi Minh begged us for support. We

32:35.606 --> 32:36.989
wouldn't give it to him. So he went to the people who 
would. He hated the Soviets, but they gave him the

32:39.033 --> 32:42.379
support. He fought the French, and he defeated 
them. And then here we come, right in their wake. If

32:48.269 --> 32:52.958
we would have done our homework and been educated, 
we would have never sent a steel helmet to Vietnam

32:48.269 --> 32:52.958
anyway. Special forces should have gone because 
that's the way to do it. We do it in a very

32:57.385 --> 33:02.095
low-profile, professional manner, small 
groups. I should have been in Vietnam, but 56,000

33:03.097 --> 33:15.942
19-year-olds should not have been that lost their 
life because a white face under a steel helmet

33:17.002 --> 33:24.368
gives every reason for a good, loyal Vietnamese, 
no matter where he is, to rally around the flag to

33:17.002 --> 33:24.368
get the hated Yankee out of his country. I was the 
intelligence officer for Delta Project. I saw

33:28.412 --> 33:36.299
that the North Vietnamese didn't start coming 
into the South until the Marines came over, until

33:28.412 --> 33:36.299
the Big Red One came over. When those steel helmets 
started arriving, the North Vietnamese built up

33:37.099 --> 33:43.685
in like numbers, and so began the Vietnam War. I 
don't think that would have happened. we wouldn't

33:46.600 --> 34:08.220
have sent those 19 year olds and it was a political 
war soldiers should not fight political wars

33:46.600 --> 34:08.220
politicians should when the politicians are not 
going to fight a political war then you fight a

33:46.600 --> 34:08.220
military war we could have won that war easily but 
we didn't because it wasn't a military victory we

33:46.600 --> 34:08.220
were interested in it was a political victory How 
did you feel coming back to the United States with

34:10.360 --> 34:14.383
the resentment against the war? I didn't care 
about that. It's a free country. And I almost got

34:18.787 --> 34:23.351
angry one day. I was in a school auditorium. And 
when we stood to say the Pledge of Allegiance to the

34:27.275 --> 34:37.744
flag, there was a black kid sitting directly in 
front of me who was long and gangly, about 6'5",

34:27.275 --> 34:37.744
obviously a young kid. And he refused to stand up. 
For a moment, I felt like pumping him on the back of

34:40.330 --> 34:45.697
his head because his mother was there and she was 
trying to get him to stand up. He wouldn't do it.

34:46.378 --> 34:50.243
Then I suddenly realized this is what we fight and 
die for. So this scumbag can sit here and act like an

34:50.283 --> 34:55.690
asshole. And I don't care. The dissenters were 
right, but for all the wrong reasons. The people

35:04.441 --> 35:08.446
who ran off to Canada were right, but for all the 
wrong reasons. They shouldn't have done it then.

35:10.537 --> 35:13.020
They should have spoken with one voice like the 
enemy did. But they may have seen something that I

35:14.361 --> 35:17.104
didn't see. Muhammad Ali, he went with his 
conscience. He did what I think is probably right.

35:24.071 --> 35:24.972
He did it the right way. He says, I'm not going to 
fight. But he didn't run off to Canada either. The

35:30.037 --> 35:31.619
fact is that our country was wrong. But at that 
time, we didn't know that. And past is always

35:33.941 --> 35:39.207
prologue and it's always 20-20 hindsight. But We 
didn't know that we were wrong then. So the

35:43.571 --> 35:45.013
dissenters were wrong. The protesters were 
wrong. They were right in the end, but they were

35:47.718 --> 35:53.689
right

35:47.718 --> 35:53.689
for the wrong reasons. But I didn't care about 
them. Nobody ever bothered me. And it's funny, in

35:58.838 --> 36:06.531
the book General Westmoreland wrote, the 
Pentagon advised me to refuse to allow him to use

35:58.838 --> 36:06.531
that story And they said the reason was because a 
lot of nuts were going to look me up, probably. But

36:12.288 --> 36:13.269
nobody ever had. I think it's because they think 
I'll probably kill them. War-crazed Vietnam vet.

36:18.794 --> 36:25.420
In all my POW efforts, some nice guy saved a movie 
star's life in Hollywood from being mugged. The

36:26.080 --> 36:29.583
guy had to change his phone to move out of town 
because he got so many death threats. I've never

36:30.144 --> 36:32.886
gotten one nut call on the phone. I've never gotten 
one letter that was a nut letter. I think it's

36:36.650 --> 36:42.520
because, I don't know why, maybe there's the aura, 
a threat, that they think I'll track them down or

36:36.650 --> 36:42.520
something. In San Francisco, people talk bad 
about the demonstrations there. I never bought a

36:47.689 --> 36:49.572
meal in San Francisco. When I came home from 
Vietnam, we were always in uniform. I used to eat

36:52.558 --> 36:55.142
breakfast there, the biggest breakfast I could 
get. And that was normally when we went over, ate

36:56.164 --> 36:59.189
breakfast. When I came back, it was usually in the 
evening. I'd eat supper there. never every time i

37:02.131 --> 37:25.742
would eat i would finish i'd get ready to pay and the 
waitress would tell me sir your meal has already

37:02.131 --> 37:25.742
been paid for and when i would ask and this happened 
god i was back across the river about 10 times

37:02.131 --> 37:25.742
because six months was each extension that you 
took and i was there for four years she would say sir

37:02.131 --> 37:25.742
your meal has already been paid for it was always 
anonymous So San Francisco was beautiful to me. I

37:28.418 --> 37:32.303
went to Las Vegas because I wanted to see a show one 
time when I'd come home to Vietnam. I didn't

37:32.323 --> 37:34.946
realize you had to have tickets months in advance. 
When I got there with my family, there was a long

37:36.428 --> 37:40.874
line, and then there was a no line. So I went up to the 
no line because I thought the long line was to buy

37:41.355 --> 37:44.259
tickets. It wasn't. The long line was people 
already had tickets. The no line was people to buy

37:47.263 --> 37:49.746
them, but it was for, like, next year. But the 
maitre d' asked me. He says, you just come back from

37:51.709 --> 37:53.491
Vietnam? And I said, yes. He said, just a minute. He 
took me and my family down. We sat right in the front

37:58.078 --> 37:59.419
row. We got everything on the house. So I was always 
treated with great respect as a soldier. I never

38:08.628 --> 38:13.573
had none of the negative experiences that I hear 
other people relate. And I think maybe it's your

38:13.613 --> 38:14.935
attitude. Who would have dared to have chastised 
me to my face? Maybe I was a crazed Vietnam veteran.

38:24.565 --> 38:26.309
Maybe I would have destroyed them. I don't know. 
Whatever it is, it didn't happen. So I didn't care

38:30.277 --> 38:31.940
about the protesters. I thought it was kind of 
humorous. When I worked on Army General Staff, I

38:32.882 --> 38:37.652
would watch the hippies, and they were totally 
disorganized. Thousands of them would form.

38:40.678 --> 38:44.346
Literally, the third human seed would form 
outside of the Pentagon. Then they would start

38:45.001 --> 38:47.344
running for the Pentagon. But they started 
running way too far back. I knew they'd never make

38:49.626 --> 38:50.607
it. They were all going to be tired out by the time 
they got to where the GSA police were. So here would

38:56.233 --> 39:05.303
come the human sea, running just like they 
probably did at the Battle of Bull Run over the

38:56.233 --> 39:05.303
green plains of the Pentagon. Then out from the 
side of the Pentagon would ride the park police

39:05.323 --> 39:11.970
with their horses, tear gas, and their billy 
clubs. And God, it was hair, eyes, and teeth all

39:12.338 --> 39:15.003
over the place. And what those poor hippies didn't 
know was inside the Pentagon, you know, there was

39:15.504 --> 39:21.275
another battalion of military police. They 
didn't stand a chance from the beginning. And then

39:23.700 --> 39:27.748
I used to laugh because they would chain 
themselves at the door of the Pentagon. And in the

39:28.235 --> 39:37.708
wintertime, it was always my suggestion that we 
help them, that we put a set of handcuffs on them,

39:28.235 --> 39:37.708
because what would happen when they got cold, 
they'd unlock the chains and they'd go get warm. So

39:37.729 --> 39:43.397
I said, let's just put our own handcuffs on them as 
long as they're chained and let them stay

39:37.729 --> 39:43.397
overnight maybe. When I went to the American 
University, I silently protested myself. I went

39:48.063 --> 39:49.986
to the American University, and it was funny. I got 
two master's degrees there, one by being a victim

39:50.046 --> 39:56.335
of a service, one was because of Abraham. The other 
was I finished school, and I never paid much

39:57.091 --> 40:02.657
attention to the regulations, so I didn't check in 
with the Army all the time. When I graduated, they

40:02.677 --> 40:06.001
didn't know I was going to graduate, so they had no 
job for me. So I had to go back for another year and

40:06.781 --> 40:10.726
take another sequence. While I was there, my 
silent protest was that I would, being an

40:10.746 --> 40:20.897
intelligence officer, I've been trained in both 
safe lock manipulation and conventional locks. I

40:21.517 --> 40:24.480
would change the locks on some of the hippies while 
they were demonstrating. I'd change the locks on

40:25.161 --> 40:26.963
their bicycles. and just change them around. And 
then until I had to go to class, I'd sit and watch

40:29.782 --> 40:38.479
them become frustrated and furious because the 
combination wasn't working or the key wouldn't

40:29.782 --> 40:38.479
work in their lock. I don't know what they ever did. 
They'd chain them up real good, and I'd chain the

40:40.463 --> 40:43.669
lock around. That's my way of protesting what they 
were doing. But I never had any vindictiveness. I

40:48.688 --> 40:51.471
didn't give a damn about that. Why did you get 
involved with your mission in 1972 when you were

40:51.491 --> 40:58.000
assigned to Panama to train Latin American 
soldiers in the special forces techniques? Yeah,

40:58.020 --> 40:59.061
it was in 72. That's a wrong thing. I went to Panama 
in 1975. I returned in 1977. I went there because

41:04.668 --> 41:09.454
the Army selected me as a commander. of Special 
Forces in Panama. It was that simple. And I must say

41:13.633 --> 41:22.046
that before I went, because you've got to realize 
I'd been on the Army General Staff, which was a puke

41:13.633 --> 41:22.046
assignment. Before that, I'd been a Command 
General of Staff, College of the University of

41:22.066 --> 41:26.492
Nebraska, a year and a half of Chinese. You know, I 
was academic. When I finally, my wife thought I was

41:30.898 --> 41:38.209
a karate instructor, because if she never saw me in 
a uniform, I went for two years to the American

41:30.898 --> 41:38.209
University. My dad was fully paid by the service. I 
told her, I said, I'm really a soldier. Someday I'm

41:42.612 --> 41:44.053
going to have to go back to work. And I did. Before I 
got ready to go to Panama, knowing what was down

41:46.336 --> 41:54.786
there, I went back up on the mountain again and made 
sure that that was exactly what I wanted to do. And I

41:55.847 --> 41:58.430
was born to be a soldier. I don't know how many 
lifetimes I've lived as a soldier, but that's what

41:58.450 --> 42:04.517
my purpose is in this life. And so I took that 
assignment. It was the best assignment in the

42:07.569 --> 42:08.710
Army. And I enjoyed it. I did a damn good job down 
there with it. And I look forward to doing it again

42:13.295 --> 42:21.224
when I was reassigned to the Pentagon and would 
have had I not been asked to retire. My next job

42:22.005 --> 42:27.771
would have been the 10th Group Commander, which is 
something I always wanted to do.

42:29.489 --> 42:55.750
um what motivated you to get involved with the 
powmia problem because i was asked by general

42:29.489 --> 42:55.750
aaron and when i thought about it it was really it 
was really shocking

42:29.489 --> 42:55.750
and depressing jesus is it possible that this 
great nation of ours could have for political

42:29.489 --> 42:55.750
reasons let live americans dropped between the 
cracks

42:57.113 --> 43:25.939
and when i thought about it and having worked as a 
chief of congressional relations i suddenly

42:57.113 --> 43:25.939
realized you damn right it was possible and once 
you get involved with it it's something you can't

42:57.113 --> 43:25.939
put down for a long time i couldn't eat a meal i 
couldn't go to sleep at night unless i thought

42:57.113 --> 43:25.939
about the condition of those men after a while you 
get fairly hardened to it I've been to Laos three

43:26.172 --> 43:30.385
times now, setting up the rescue. We will rescue 
them. We're going to do it soon. But it certainly is

43:35.723 --> 43:37.466
possible. I used to not think that the president 
even went to the bathroom. I thought he was totally

43:40.911 --> 43:44.536
invulnerable to all of the human frailties. 
That's wrong. He is only going to do what, like any

43:47.120 --> 43:55.633
other servant, what we make him do. And that's why 
the president has discovered POWs in 1983. Not

43:59.179 --> 44:04.667
because they didn't know about them, but because 
the American people has finally brought it to

44:05.018 --> 44:28.950
national attention to the point where all the 
politicians see they better start looking at it so

44:05.018 --> 44:28.950
i got interested in it because i was invited i would 
have loved to have forgotten about the vietnam war

44:05.018 --> 44:28.950
i was very happy in panama i didn't even think about 
vietnam and to revisit a lot of those experiences

44:05.018 --> 44:28.950
was not pleasant for me And to, I don't want to lance 
the festering wound of war that has been healing

44:29.538 --> 44:37.226
for 10 years now. But if you must lance it to let it 
heal cleanly, then let's lance it. This issue is

44:46.235 --> 44:47.917
much like a cancer. The politicians are like 
people who, even though the sickness has been

44:49.038 --> 44:54.263
diagnosed, They don't want to hear it. They don't 
want to treat it because the treatment is onerous

44:56.558 --> 45:00.985
and very difficult. But it's a cancer that I think 
can strangle our moral standards in this country.

45:08.117 --> 45:13.886
If they strangle our moral standards, if it erodes 
that underpinning, what's going to hold us up as a

45:08.117 --> 45:13.886
country? So I think that it is so important that 
like a patient who does have a cancer or sickness we

45:18.205 --> 45:43.588
do whatever we have to do to treat it and to get well 
and that's why i will as anyone who loves a relative

45:18.205 --> 45:43.588
and i love this country i'm going to continue to 
